title: For Sale:  Colt Official Police Post-war first year production 99%+
location: Spartanburg, Greenville, Woodruff, Greenville, South Carolina
postcontent:
Colt Official Police Post-war first year production - 1947 in 99%" condition

Made from 1947 to 1969.

Colt decided to rename the Army Special to more reflect the actual buyers of the gun, so the Army Special name was changed to the Official Police.

The 1947 post-war version had a ramped and serrated front sight, a new shaped hammer with grooves, and the new cylinder retention system.



That was just what the gun was, THE official police issue revolver for a great many police departments like the New York City Police, Boston Police, and Federal agencies like the FBI and Treasury Department.

The Official Police would serve as a prime police issue gun into the 1960s, and was highly favored by private guard services, industrial plant guards, and civilian gun owners wanting a powerful and strong revolver.

Up for sale is my 458 socom AR. It is a stout little elephant gun. It is also the perfect hog hunting gun. This caliber is basically a modern day 45-70 government ballistics wise. Take for example, you are sitting on your porch relaxing after watching the big game. Suddenly a terrorist shows up, having grown tired of religious freedom and tolerance we have here in 'merica. Worse yet, he is wearing stage 3 body armor. You reckon you could satisfy his curiosity on whether his god exists. You will want to give them the answer that only a 458 socom can provide. If he manages to live (while wearing stage 3 body armor) you just broke every bone in his upper body. 

So after all this wonderful abilities this rifle has, why am i selling it? Because i am not a brave man im afraid. I am ashamed to say i let the commies win. By Commies, of course, i mean my wife. She claims i have too many guns already and dont need one to hunt elephants. I disagree. What if the tide rolls or the eagle goes to war?  I am madly in love with my captor so i will comply. So if you read this far, i hope you at least got a good smirk going on. I know i will once she sees this ad and proceeds to bonk me on the head. Here is a quick list to recap

Pros:

Lower completely interchangeble with standard AR 5.56 uppers. Just swap and go.

5.56 magazines can be used just fine with the 458 socom ammo. Just single stack instead of double. Use metal one magazines peferably as plastic ones tend to jam.

Energy transfer is impressive from this platform. Give a quick peek to Iraqveteran8888 on youtube in regards to this caliber if you would like an idea of its power.

Cons:

Ammo is not readily available on shelf.

Ammo is also about 2 dollars a round.


So email me or call/text REDACTED

I've started trapping and in I'm serious need of a 22 pistol.. I'm open to almost anything as long as it's in good condition, reliable, and able to kill furbearers!  I could possibly be open to a small .22 rifle as long as it's compact and easy to carry. 

This is an awesome little .38 special that I came across.. I don't really know it's history and I'm not an expert on guns, but I know that it shoot great! I've only put around 12 bullets thru it so far, but I have no complaints. I was told that it was not shot very much by the last owner and set on a closet for a long time. title: For Sale:  Rare Remington Model 37 Rangemaster Target Rifle         22 LR 511 514 Winchester 52 75 Stevens Anschutz
postcontent: I have for auction a fantastic Remington Model 37 Rangemaster Bolt Action Clip Fed Repeating Target Rifle, chambered for .22 Long rifle cartridges. This beautiful vintage Remington bearing serial number 04775, stamped with a “ XRR “ date code was manufactured in December of 1946 documented by information published from the Remington factory barrel date coding system. The rifle in our auction photographs was designed as Remington’s top of the line rim fire target rifle. Remington target rifles were very competitive in matches all over the world, and the quality and workmanship in there rifles was unequaled. The over all condition of the rifle in our auction is exceptional; Target rifles were generally used a lot during this time period when shooting was in its prime so to speak. It is seldom to see target rifles from this vintage, that still remain in really nice over-all condition. This particular Remington Model 37 still retains virtually all of the Remington factory applied blued metal finish throughout showing some very light signs of wear from use. The rifle looks almost like new, has a perfect bore, still functions just like new, with a nice firm lock up, and a great trigger pull. This is definitely one of the nicest Rangemaster rifles that we have been privileged to offer for sale here on Gun Broker. Those of you who know your Remington target rifles, will certainly see this as a very nice clean example for its age. The rifle features a 28 inch heavy "Match Grade Target Barrel", is chambered for .22 Long rifle rim fire cartridges, and comes complete with one Remington factory original 5 round magazine installed. The factory Remington Walnut wood stock is in excellent condition retaining virtually all of the original factory applied finish. The rifle has a couple very minor handling marks as shown in our auction photographs, however compared to most of this vintage the rifle is in great condition otherwise, and still presents itself beautifully. The rifle has had the barrel stabilized as you can see, this practice was not uncommon with target shooters to increase accuracy on target rifles. This fantastic vintage Remington Model 37 would be a wonderful investment piece, a great addition to any collection, or would also make a great rifle for the range. For those of our viewers a little less know-legible on the Remington Model 37 Rifles they were Remington’s top of the line rim fire target rifle, and were designed and manufactured with the most stringent quality controls to compete with Winchester’s famous Model 52 Target Rifles. The rifle in  auction has the factory original Remington supplied sights. The rear sight was uniquely designed to mount to a Scope base with six index points for eye relief therefore making adjustments as well as complete removal quick and easy as well as precision lockup keeping the sight at zero at all times. The rifle also has a specially developed Remington multi-aperture that allows the shooter one of six different size apertures all in one sight without removing or changing any parts. You simply rotate the desired aperture into position. The front sight is a Redfield globe sight with interchangeable apertures affixed to a special base for quick removal. These sights were specific to the Remington Model 37 Target Rifles, and are nearly impossible to find, since this rifle comes complete with the sights, it is simply a huge bonus! In addition folks, the rifle comes with the original Remington factory supplied scope blocks. What a great package! If the winner of this auction would like to fit this rifle with a fine John Unertl or Lyman Target scope we would be happy to assist, I have contacts that could supply several fine scopes that would fit this rifle at an additional cost. The Winchester Model 52 rifles were better marketed by Winchester, therefore they outsold the Remington Model 37 Rangemaster somewhere around a ratio of 5 to 1 or more, therefore today making these fine Model 37 Remington target rifles highly sought after as collector’s items & investments alike since there were so few produced. Finding an example that still remains in great overall condition like the rifle in our auction is very, very rare indeed. This would be a great addition to any fine Remington or gun collection
